claim.claim-text:
1. Curved eyewear, comprising: a curved lens comprised of a central field-of-view portion and a peripheral field-of-view portion, the curved lens having an electrically variable spectral transmittance in the central field-of-view portion and the peripheral field-of-view portion, the curved lens having a diameter between 120 millimeters and 200 millimeters;
a lens control system comprising at least a memory, a pattern generator and a driver associated with the curved eyewear that controls the electrically variable spectral transmittance of the curved lens; and
a frame configured to retain the curved lens relative to a face of a wearer.

12. Curved eyewear, comprising: a curved lens comprised of at least two portions, a first portion comprised of a first central field-of-view portion and a first peripheral field of view portion and a second portion comprised of a second central field-of-view portion and a second peripheral field-of-view portion, the curved lens having a diameter between 120 millimeters and 200 millimeters;
the first central field-of-view portion and the first peripheral field-of-view portion of the first portion electrically switchable from a first light transmittance state to a second light transmittance state; the second portion electrically switchable from the first light transmittance state to the second light transmittance state; a lens control system comprising at least a memory, a pattern generator and a lens driver associated with the curved eyewear that controls electrically switching from the first light transmittance stale to a second light transmittance state; and
a frame configured to retain the curved lens in a curved orientation.

20. Curved eyewear, comprising: a curved lens comprised of a central field-of-view portion and a peripheral field-of-view portion, the central field-of-view portion and the peripheral field-of-view portion are electrically switchable between a substantially light obscuring state and a substantially transparent state using liquid crystals, the curved lens constructed from a flat polymer that is shatter resistant, the curved lens having a diameter between 120 millimeters and 200 millimeters;
a lens control system comprising at least a memory, a pattern generator and a lens driver, the lens driver controls switching the lens between the substantially light obscuring slate and the substantially transparent state at an adjustable frequency;
a power source effective for switching between the substantially light obscuring state and the substantially transparent state in response to the lens driver;
a curved frame comprised of a lens curving channel, the lens curving channel effective for maintain the curved lens in a curved orientation for an increased peripheral field of view, having the diameter between 120 millimeters and 200 millimeters.
